column11: Current ECB President Mario Draghi's term ends this fall (The Economist, Bloomberg, The Financial Times). The ECB president is appointed by the European Council, acting by a qualified majority (The European Central Bank, The European Council).

column6: Too much turmoil to make an important decision due to brexit

On September 17, 2019, the European Parliament voted via secret ballot to recommend Ms. Lagarde to the position of ECB President, with 394 in favor, 206 opposed, and 49 abstentions. If confirmed by the European Council in its October summit, she will succeed Mario Draghi and would become the first woman to serve as ECB President.

Christine Lagarde (born in France) is the only nomination for the ECB presidency. Mario Draghi's, the incumbent, tenure comes to an end 31 October 2019. The procedure is that the formal appointment must be made by the European Council, which is only scheduled to meet 17 - 18 October 2019.

Didn’t see that coming! “European leaders nominated Christine Lagarde, head of the International Monetary Fund, to become the next president of the European Central Bank. Her nomination must be formally approved before she takes over from Mario Draghi, whose term ends on October 31st. The leaders also nominated Ursula von der Leyen, Germany’s defence minister, to become president of the European Commission. “

Lagarde's nomination was announced in a tweet by European Council president Donald Tusk following a meeting between leaders that has lasted since Sunday. While her appointment still needs to be confirmed by the European Parliament—Tuesday's vote, from the heads of European states, is the first step—the nomination sets her up to be the first female head of European monetary policy. https://www.forbes.com/sites/maggiemcgrath/2019/07/02/imf-head-christine-lagarde-nominated-to-run-the-european-central-bank/#44401b265826

And from the Economist this morning - no clarity yet and how this is tied into other appointments: “This morning European Union leaders convene for a meeting that was never meant to take place. They had gathered in Brussels on Sunday to discuss the allocation of big jobs like the presidencies of the European Commission (the EU’s executive), the European Council (the collective heads of government), the European Parliament and the European Central Bank. Also in the mix was the role of High Representative for foreign affairs and security policy, a sort of EU foreign minister. Yet they could not reach a deal. A package by which Frans Timmermans, a Dutch social democrat, would become Commission president was backed by Angela Merkel and Emmanuel Macron but opposed by other leaders. Central European governments in particular objected to Mr Timmermans’s robust defence of liberal values. Today EU leaders will try to find a blend of candidates that tick all boxes. Mr Timmermans is not yet out of the running, but leaders are eyeing alternatives.“

From the Economist: “Bank-watchers are accustomed to trying to anticipate the ECB’s monetary-policy actions. Though inflation has been disappointingly low, little is expected from the central bank’s meeting today, beyond the details of its new lending facility to banks. A bigger decision hangs over the institution this year, one that will be made by politicians not bankers: who will replace Mario Draghi as the ECB’s president? Leading contenders include the heads of the French and German central banks, the current and former governor of the Bank of Finland, and an insider already on the bank’s executive board. Politicians know their choice is an important one, given the ECB’s role in propping up the euro area’s economy. But with the job only one among several vacancies at the top of European institutions this year, there is plenty of scope for horse-trading too. This decision might defy prediction.“

Finland: Olli Rehn and Erkki Liikanen both have a good chance and would be a good neutral choice for the bigger / permanent members. France: Francois Villeroy de Galhau has a chance, but considering the past presidents from the Netherlands, France, and Italy other nations will likley want a turn. Coeure is also mentioned in the press but, as a sitting board member, he is not eligible for reappointment. Germany: Bundesbank President Jens Weidmann has antagonized many. He publicly opposed the ECB’s stimulus program, credited with reviving growth, and got into a public fight with Italy’s prime minister over fiscal discipline. Ireland: Philip Lane, the main contender, will likely become Chief Economist. Netherlands: Klaas Knot - same as above, Netherlands has had the president recently.

Front Runners: 1. Erkki Liikanen, EU Veteran. The 68-year-old stepped down from his post as Finland’s central-bank governor in July, and would bring decades of Brussels experience to the top of the ECB as governments try to solve the single currency’s structural shortcomings. *** 2. Francois Villeroy de Galhau, German-Speaking Banker. France’s central-bank governor is considered a serious contender if governments balk at appointing a German. Since taking over at the Bank of France in 2015, Villeroy has stuck close to Draghi’s line backing continued stimulus. 3. Jens Weidmann. Francophile Hawk. Weidmann became the Bundesbank’s youngest-ever president in 2011 after his predecessor resigned to protest ECB bond purchases. Now 50, he’s taken a hard line against loose monetary policy, earning him respect at home but criticism from Draghi for his perceived “nein zu allem”—no to everything—attitude. *** 4. Olli Rehn, Finnish Eurocrat. Rehn, 56, may be one of the newer faces in European central banking, but he’s been involved in economic affairs for years. As EU commissioner in charge of the euro during the region’s debt crisis, he was a strong advocate of ﬁscal discipline before returning to Finnish politics in 2015 as economy minister and overseeing the country’s emergence from a three-year recession. *** 5. Benoit Coeure, Markets Maestro. Coeure, 49, is already on the ECB's Executive Board with a non-renewable eight-year term that runs until the end of 2019. He's highly respected though, and it's possible a way could be found to shift him to the presidency. He's one of the architects behind quantitative easing and is responsible for markets, so he certainly has the necessary experience. 6. Klaas Knot, Dutch Hope. The 51-year-old head of the Dutch central bank is one of the youngest members on the Governing Council. He’s also typically on the same page as Weidmann on the topic of monetary stimulus, speaking out against keeping asset purchases going for too long. 7. Klaus Regling. The Underwriter. One of the architects of the euro, Regling spent a decade at the German Finance Ministry where he helped prepare for economic and monetary union. In his current position leading the European Stability Mechanism, a backstop for countries in financial crisis, the 68-year-old has had close insight into the euro area’s existential woes. 8. Christine Lagarde. Trailblazing Globetrotter. Lagarde made her name breaking tradition in a world of predominantly male economic policy makers. As French finance minister from 2007-2011, she was the first woman to hold such a post in a Group of 8 country, and since then has been the first female head of the International Monetary Fund. Lagarde would also be the first woman to head the ECB and the first president without an economics degree. ________________________ COMMENTS: I heard that Ireland is out. Lagarde may be on the lookout for another big assignment. Besides there was Trichet before.
